start/end.\n\nI think the most feasible approach is to abstract the edge cases to properties about permissions and resource access, as that is the core of the given model. For example:\n- Edge case 1 (exact same time as existing slot) -> two operations targeting the same resource with the same grant? Or maybe a resource cannot be accessed by two different initiators at the same time? So safety: For all operations, no two operations have the same target resource and overlapping time? But no time.\n- Instead, we can say that a resource cannot be accessed simultaneously by two different initiators. That is captured by the fact that resource\'s accessible set is fixed? Not.\n\nGiven the time, I will make a pragmatic decision: I will define a helper sig Slot with fields start, end, and then define that each REQ_SCHED_01 operation corresponds to a Slot via a field? But we cannot add fields to REQ_SCHED_01. We can add a relation: sig OpSlotRel { op: REQ_SCHED_01, slot: Slot }. But that is another helper. Then we can assert that for any op, the slots associated with its target resources have no overlap among themselves and with slots of other operations? That gets messy.\n\nI think the best course is to ignore the temporal aspects and instead interpret the edge cases in terms of resource access conflicts. For example, "slot created at the exact same time as an existing slot" could be interpreted as two operations that have the same target resource and the same grant. That would be a conflict because two operations might try to schedule the same resource with the same permission at the same time. So safety: No two operations have the same target and same grant. But that\'s a global assertion, not per operation. But we can assert for all op, there is no other op\' such that op\'.target & op.target != none and op\'.grant = op.grant. That would be a safety property: no two operations share a resource with the same grant (to avoid conflict). That covers edge case 1. Edge case 2: