tateSlots {\n    state: one State,\n    slot: one Slot\n}\n\nBut then we can have multiple StateSlots for the same state and different slots.\n\nNow we need to ensure that for each state, there is no overlapping slots. We can write a predicate:\npred noOverlap[s: State] {\n    all disj ss1, ss2: StateSlots | ss1.state = s and ss2.state = s implies\n        not (lt[ss1.slot.start, ss2.slot.end] and lt[ss2.slot.start, ss1.slot.end])\n}\n\nBut we need to be careful with Int bounds. We\'ll assume Int is defined with range.\n\nNow the safety assertions:\n\nassert ec_safe_1 {\n    all op: REQ_SCHED_01 |\n        // In the post state of any operation, no two slots have exactly the same start and end\n        no disj ss1, ss2: StateSlots |\n            ss1.state = op.post and ss2.state = op.post and\n            ss1.slot.start = ss2.slot.start and ss1.slot.end = ss2.slot.end\n}\n\nassert ec_safe_2 {\n    all op: REQ_SCHED_01 |\n        // In the post state, no two slots overlap\n        noOverlap[op.post]\n}\n\nassert ec_safe_3 {\n    all op: REQ_SCHED_01 |\n        // If a slot is created that fits between two existing slots (i.e., starts after one ends and before another begins),\n        // then the post state must still have no overlaps. We cannot directly check because we don\'t have the new slot\'s interval.\n        // But we can assert that if there is a slot in post that does not exist in pre, then its interval does not cause overlap.\n        // We can use a helper: suppose we have a new slot in post that is not in pre.\n        // To detect new slot, we need to compare StateSlots.\n        // Simple approach: if a slot exists in post but not in pre, then for that slot, there is no other slot in post that overlaps.\n        // This is captured by noOverlap anyway.\n        noOverlap[op.post]\n}\n\nThe third assertion is redundant. To differentiate, we can add a condition that if the operation\'s target resources are such that they have intervals that fit exactly between two existing intervals, then the operation is allowed (i.e., noOverlap holds). But again we need interval data for target resources.\n\nGiven the instructions say "derive the safety property semantically from the edge case text", I think we should interpret edge case 3 as a safety property that the system does not erroneously reject a valid non-overlapping slot. Since we cannot model rejection, we can assert that such an operation is possible (exists), not that it holds for all. But the instruction says "assert ec_safe_N { all op: REQ_SCHED_01 | <must never be violated> }". So it must be a property that every operation must satisfy. For edge case 3, maybe the property is that if the operation\'s target is a slot that does not overlap with any existing slot in pre state, then the operation will not cause an overlap in post state. That is a conditional safety invariant. To express that, we need to know the pre state\'s slots and the new slot\'s interval. We can use the StateSlots and the operation\'s target. We can assume that each target resource is associated with a Slot via a field in the operation? Not present. But we can create a relation from Resource to Slot: each resource has a slot (maybe a single slot). That would be a static mapping. Then we can assert: for all op, for all r in op.target, let s be the slot of r. Then if in op.pre, there is no other slot s\' such that s\' overlaps with s, then in op.post, there is no overlap. That is a safety property. We\'ll need a mapping Resource->Slot. We can add a one sig SlotMap { resource: Resource, slot: Slot } but that would allow multiple per resource. Better to have a field in Resource? Not allowed. So we can do a relation: slotOf: Resource -> Slot. We can define a sig SlotAssignment { resource: Resource, slot: Slot } and fact that each Resource has at most one slot. That works.\n\nLet\'s implement:\nsig SlotAssignment { resource: Resource, slot: Slot }\nfact { all r: Resource | lone sa: SlotAssignment | sa