tState are just State. But the model uses "pre: one PreState" which might be a typo and should be "pre: one State". Given the inconsistency, we should adapt: use the fields as given: pre and post are of types that are one of the State atoms (Pre1, Post1, Post2). Since the model context says "State atoms (Pre1…PreN, Post1…PostN) are the only valid State values", we can treat pre and post as State atoms.\n\nGiven the edge cases are about scheduling slots, we need to map "slot" to Resource? Resources might represent time slots? Possibly each Resource has an owner and accessible set. But time slots would have start/end times. The model doesn\'t have time. So we need to introduce minimal helper sigs to represent time or slots. The instructions say: "If the edge case requires a new concept (e.g., a concurrency model, a size constraint, an error state), introduce a minimal helper sig BEFORE the assertion. Keep helpers to 1–2 fields maximum." So we can introduce helper sigs for time slots. We can create a sig TimeSlot with fields start and end? But we only have Int for numbers. We can use Int for time values. However, we also have no ordering relation on resources. So we can add a sig Slot that has start and end Int fields, and maybe a day field for multi-day slots. Then we can assert safety properties about slot creation conflicts.\n\nBut the operation REQ_SCHED_01 is about an operation on resources, not necessarily slot creation. The edge cases describe "when a slot is created" and "user attempts to create a slot". So we can interpret the REQ_SCHED_01 operation as a slot creation operation. Then target would be the slot being created? But target is set of Resource (some Resource). So we can assume that Resource includes slots. To model time, we need to add a sig Slot that extends Resource? But Resource is abstract? Actually from the declared list: "sig Resource [owner: one Actor, accessible: set Actor]". So Resource is a sig with fields. We can create a new sig Slot that 